5 Calibration Analysis
The tightness of all bounds depends on the classifier’s calibration: if the confidence scores are systematically overconfident, the empirical risk at a given underestimates the true risk.
We assess calibration using Expected Calibration Error (ECE; Guo et al. 2017) with 15 bins. SetFit’s raw softmax outputs are poorly calibrated: ECE0.515 on MASSIVE and 0.423 on NyayaBench v2, with confidence scores clustered in while actual accuracy exceeds 90%.
Temperature scaling (Guo et al., 2017)—optimizing on the calibration set via NLL minimization—reduces ECE to 0.040 on MASSIVE (, improvement) and 0.077 on NyayaBench v2 (, improvement).
Why calibration matters despite distribution-free bounds. A natural question is why calibration analysis appears in a paper whose bounds are distribution-free. The RCPS guarantee holds regardless of calibration—this is a strength of the framework. However, calibration directly affects which operating points are achievable. With poorly calibrated scores (ECE0.515), the confidence values are compressed into a narrow band , so small changes in cause large coverage swings, making the risk–coverage curve steep and the feasible region narrow. After temperature scaling (ECE0.040), scores spread across , the risk–coverage curve becomes smoother, and a wider range of values yield useful operating points. We apply RCPS to the raw (uncalibrated) scores throughout this paper, as the guarantee is exact in that case; the calibration analysis serves to explain why certain values emerge and to guide practitioners on whether investing in calibration improves the practical utility of the guarantee.
6 Experiments
6.1 Setup
Classifier. We use SetFit (Tunstall et al., 2022) with an all-MiniLM-L6-v2 backbone (22M parameters), trained with 8 examples per class via contrastive learning followed by a classification head.
Benchmarks. (1) MASSIVE (FitzGerald et al., 2023): 1,102 test examples, 8 intent classes for personal agents (weather, reminders, lights, music, alarms, email, calendar, general). (2) NyayaBench v2: 280 test examples, 20 W5H2 intent classes derived from real agentic usage patterns across voice assistants, smart home devices, and productivity agents. (3) CLINC-150 (Larson et al., 2019): 22,500 examples, 150 intent classes; we use simulated confidence scores matching published SetFit accuracy distributions to create a synthetic benchmark validation at scale. (4) Banking77 (Casanueva et al., 2020): 13,083 examples, 77 fine-grained banking intent classes; similarly simulated.222CLINC-150 and Banking77 use simulated confidence scores calibrated to match published accuracy distributions for each dataset. This synthetic approach validates that our bounds generalize beyond the two primary benchmarks where we have real SetFit predictions.
Protocol. Each benchmark is split 50/50 into calibration and test sets (stratified by class, seed 42). We sweep thresholds in at 0.01 increments. All nine bound families are evaluated at and (18 configurations each). Transfer methods (PAC-Bayes transfer, Transfer-Informed Betting) are evaluated on NyayaBench v2 using MASSIVE as the source domain.
