Implication for deployment. Per-intent guarantees are desirable but require either (a) much larger datasets (roughly calibration examples per intent), or (b) hierarchical approaches that pool information across similar intents. For typical agent caching deployments with 10–20 intents, the aggregate guarantee with marginal risk (Section 2) provides the most practical safety certificate, supplemented by monitoring of per-intent error rates without formal guarantees.
6.6 Conformal Prediction Baseline Comparison
A natural question is why we use RCPS (risk-controlling prediction sets in the selective prediction sense) rather than standard split-conformal prediction (Vovk et al., 2005). The two frameworks solve fundamentally different problems, and we provide a rigorous comparison to clarify this distinction.
Conformal prediction guarantees that the true class belongs to a prediction set with probability . Using the score function and the split-conformal quantile , the prediction set is . This guarantees coverage (true class ) but produces a set of candidate classes, not a single prediction.
Selective prediction / RCPS guarantees that the risk of the single predicted class is bounded: . This produces a single prediction with a risk guarantee.
Table 5 compares both approaches on MASSIVE and NyayaBench v2.
The key distinction is operational. Conformal prediction at on MASSIVE achieves 90.4% coverage but with an average prediction set size of 1.67 classes—meaning many queries receive multiple candidate intents. In a caching system, one cannot cache a set of intents; the system must commit to a single response. Selective prediction at the same achieves 94.0% coverage with a single prediction and a guaranteed risk of 6.3%.
On NyayaBench v2 (20 classes), the distinction is even starker: at , conformal prediction sets average 4.77 classes—nearly a quarter of the label space—while selective prediction provides a single-prediction guarantee.
Figure 6 visualizes this tradeoff, showing that the two methods offer complementary guarantees: conformal controls set-valued coverage, while RCPS/selective controls point-prediction risk. For applications requiring single predictions (caching, classification deployment, automated decision-making), RCPS is the appropriate framework.
7 Progressive Trust as Selective Prediction
