The coverage–guarantee gap. On MASSIVE, the empirical optimal threshold (, 88% coverage from uncertified sweeping) is close to the LTT-guaranteed threshold (, 94.0% coverage at ). Remarkably, the guaranteed operating point actually has higher coverage than the empirical one, because the empirical sweep chose a conservative point without formal justification. This demonstrates that formal guarantees need not sacrifice coverage.
On NyayaBench v2, the gap is larger: the guarantee requires with only 14.4% coverage even with PAC-Bayes transfer. This “price of the guarantee” motivates either (a) collecting more calibration data, or (b) accepting that the cascade must defer aggressively on hard 20-class tasks—a principled conclusion rather than an ad hoc engineering choice.
8 Related Work
Semantic caching for LLMs. GPTCache (Bang et al., 2023) uses embedding similarity with a fixed threshold; vCache (Schroeder et al., 2025) adds LLM-based verification of borderline hits; SemanticALLI (Chillara et al., 2026) caches reasoning traces; LangCache (Gill et al., 2025) uses domain-specific embeddings. All select thresholds empirically without finite-sample guarantees. Our work provides the missing statistical foundation.
Agentic plan caching. APC (Zhang et al., 2025) caches plan templates and adapts them with LLM calls. RAGCache (Jin et al., 2024) caches retrieval-augmented generation outputs. Both treat caching as a systems optimization; we treat it as a selective prediction problem with formal safety constraints.
Conformal prediction and RCPS. Split-conformal prediction (Vovk et al., 2005) guarantees marginal coverage of prediction sets; RCPS (Bates et al., 2021) generalizes this to risk-controlling prediction sets; LTT (Angelopoulos and Bates, 2022) extends RCPS with fixed-sequence testing that eliminates the union-bound penalty. Selective classification (Geifman and El-Yaniv, 2017) studies the coverage–accuracy tradeoff. A key distinction—often elided in the literature—is between set-valued conformal guarantees (true class prediction set) and point-prediction risk guarantees (risk on the selected prediction). We provide a rigorous empirical comparison (Section 6.6, Table 5) showing that conformal prediction sets average 1.67–4.77 classes at –, making them unsuitable for applications requiring single predictions. We ablate nine bound families for the selective prediction setting and introduce Transfer-Informed Betting as a novel cross-domain mechanism.
Betting and e-processes. Testing by betting (Shafer, 2021) and confidence sequences (Howard et al., 2021) provide anytime-valid inference. Waudby-Smith and Ramdas (2024) show that betting-based bounds dominate classical concentration inequalities for bounded random variables. Our contribution is extending WSR betting to cross-domain settings via warm-started wealth processes (Transfer-Informed Betting, Theorem 1), which has not been studied previously.
PAC-Bayes bounds. Classic PAC-Bayes theory (Catoni, 2007) provides bounds that can be tighter than Hoeffding when an informative prior is available. We apply PAC-Bayes with cross-domain transfer to selective prediction, and additionally show that betting-based transfer achieves comparable performance via a different mechanism.
Calibration. Temperature scaling (Guo et al., 2017) is the standard post-hoc calibration method. We use it as a diagnostic tool but apply RCPS to raw scores, since the guarantee is exact regardless of calibration.
9 Conclusion
We have shown that the choice of concentration inequality, multiple-testing correction, and cross-domain transfer mechanism has a dramatic effect on the achievable coverage under finite-sample safety guarantees for selective prediction. Through a comprehensive ablation of nine bound families across four benchmark datasets, including novel contributions in testing by betting with cross-domain transfer, we establish the following practical recipe:
-
•
Large calibration sets (): Use WSR Betting + LTT or LTT + Empirical Bernstein. WSR betting adapts to the observed loss distribution; LTT eliminates the union-bound factor. On MASSIVE, both achieve 94.0% guaranteed coverage at .
-
•
Small calibration sets with transfer (): Use Transfer-Informed Betting (our novel method, Theorem 1). The warm-started wealth process exploits source domain risk profiles to concentrate bounds faster, matching PAC-Bayes transfer coverage on NyayaBench v2 while providing the additional benefit of anytime validity.
-
•
Small calibration sets without transfer: Use PAC-Bayes- with an uninformative prior, which leverages its faster rate.
-
•
Exact small-risk bounds: Use Clopper-Pearson + LTT when the classifier is highly accurate (), achieving tightness over Hoeffding.
-
•
Distribution shift concerns: Use Wasserstein DRO, which explicitly budgets for shift at the cost of lower coverage.
These guarantees formalize the progressive trust model for agentic systems: the RCPS certificate determines when a cached chain can safely graduate from LLM-supervised to autonomous execution. The progressive trust simulation (Section 6.3) quantifies this trajectory: LTT enables semi-autonomous operation (62% coverage) at and autonomous operation (94% coverage) at , while Hoeffding remains infeasible until . As calibration data accumulates, the bounds tighten, coverage increases, and the system becomes simultaneously cheaper and safer.
Limitations. The marginal risk formulation (Eq. 1) averages over the full query distribution; as shown in Section 6.5, per-intent subgroup guarantees require substantially more data ( per class) and are infeasible for most intent classes at typical dataset sizes. PAC-Bayes transfer assumes the source and target risk profiles are related, which may not hold for domains with very different intent distributions. The one violation observed at for PAC-Bayes transfer (Section 6.3) highlights the fragility of very small calibration sets. All bounds assume i.i.d. calibration data (except DRO, which relaxes this partially).
Future work. Transfer-Informed Betting (Section 4.3) naturally extends to online settings: as new target queries arrive, the wealth process updates continuously, enabling anytime-valid trust certificates without fixed calibration sets. Multi-source transfer—blending risk profiles from multiple agent domains—may further tighten small- bounds. Hierarchical subgroup guarantees that pool information across related intents could bridge the gap between aggregate and per-class safety. Extending the betting framework to handle non-stationary query distributions (via discounted wealth processes) is a natural next step for production deployment.
